x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><b>J.J. Abrams</b> =
and his Bad Robot production company are closing a new multiyear film and T=
V overall deal with Warner Bros., per two sources familiar with the negotia=
tions. The details are still being finalized, but one thing is clear: The a=
rrangement will represent a massive pay cut from Abrams=E2=80=99 blockbuste=
r 2019 contract, which cost Warners about $250 million and included incenti=
ves for creating film franchises, which never happened. Warner Bros., then =
owned by AT&amp;T and racing to launch HBO Max and compete in streaming, wo=
n the resulting five-year pact after a multi-studio bidding war. <b>John St=
ankey</b>, then running WarnerMedia, declared he was =E2=80=9Cdelighted=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cextremely excited=E2=80=9D about the agreement. <br/> <=
br/>Today, of course, that Bad Robot deal is considered by many to be the b=
iggest bust of the Peak TV era. Abrams
under-delivered (see below), but extracting that kind of money from a deep-=
pocketed studio is hardly the fault of the talent. The studios? With 20/20 =
hindsight, some of those overall deals now look downright foolish. The rise=
 of Netflix, the endless supply of cheap debt, and the flawed strategies of=
 legacy media companies fueled the content bubble=E2=80=94not the stars and=
 showrunners who gladly took the millions. Now, as total series on the air =
have dropped from more than 600 in 2022 to 516 in 2023 to far fewer this ye=
ar, the once-common $5 million-a-year overall deal for a mid-tier writer-pr=
oducer has become $1 million, if you can get one at all. Meanwhile, studios=
 are taking stock of the cost of their former largesse.  <br/> <br/>So, whi=
ch deals were the winners and losers of Peak TV? Most of the nine-figure cl=
ub was signed with the intention that they would deliver multiple hits. Few=
 did. And volume alone isn=E2=80=99t always a good barometer. <i>Bridgerton=
, </i>for example, is a
global franchise that likely makes <i>both </i>of <b>Shonda Rhimes</b>=E2=
=80=99 nine-figure contracts worth the dough for Netflix, even if she doesn=
=E2=80=99t deliver another hit. On the flipside, Netflix is still waiting f=
or an R.O.I. from <i>Power </i>creator <b>Courtney Kemp</b>. Disney also ap=
pears to have swung and missed with its eight-figure deal with <b>Ron Moore=
</b>. <br/> <br/>Let=E2=80=99s do it, a Peak TV postmortem, assessing the b=
est and worst TV deals of the 2019-23 era, with the benefit of 2024 hindsig=
ht. Many people got rich, some got <i>very</i> rich, and a precious few jus=
tified the outsize paydays. <br/></td>
